-- WP10 (docs/spec/WASM-SEMANTICS.md §1) — #553 Stage A: the SECOND silent S0, and the
-- one that proves the filed root cause was incomplete.
--
-- `eager_global_call_hidden.mdk` (its peer) is the CALL-HIDDEN arm: the eager-init topo
-- sort loses its edge because the read hides inside a callee, so the remedy WP10 states —
-- "a closure that follows calls" — would catch it. THIS fixture involves NO CALL AT ALL.
-- The read is a direct subterm of the eager binding's own rhs:
--
--   part = src.[lo..3]        -- `lo` is read RIGHT HERE, no function in sight
--   lo = 1                    -- ...but declared later
--
-- and it was still wrong, because `eagerVars` (compiler/backend/emit_support.mdk) DROPPED
-- SUBTERMS OF THE NODE IT WAS STANDING ON: its `CStringSlice a lo hi _` arm descended only
-- the receiver `a` and discarded `lo`/`hi` wholesale. No call-graph closure fixes that —
-- the edge is not hidden behind anything, it was simply never scanned. It is a
-- STRUCTURAL-COMPLETENESS bug, not an algorithmic one.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines BEFORE the fix (2026-07-17, origin/main 01eadd60):
--   eval   -> el           (correct)
--   native -> hel, exit 0  (a WRONG ANSWER with no diagnostic — the S0)
-- After Stage A restored `lo`/`hi` to the scan, native answers `el` and this is green.
--
-- ⭐ The decisive control is `eager_global_list_slice.mdk`: the IDENTICAL program on a
-- List receiver, whose neighbouring `CListSlice` arm DID descend `lo`/`hi` and was green
-- the whole time. Same shape, adjacent arm, one wrong — which is what turned "eagerVars
-- is call-blind" into "eagerVars is also structurally incomplete", a different claim.
--
-- Keep this fixture green. If it regresses, an arm of `eagerVars` has stopped descending
-- an eagerly-evaluated subterm again, and the failure mode is a silent wrong answer at
-- exit 0 — the class no parity gate and no allocation-graded perf gate can see.

src = "hello"

part = src.[lo..3]

lo = 1

main = part
